segments.text: I am interviewing Nelson M. Duller.
He's a professor of physics.
He lives at 818 North Rosemary in Bryan.
Now, as a matter of formality, I'll ask, you know, I have to ask your name.
Okay.
So what's your name, Dr. Duller?
Nelson M. Duller, and as you say, I'm a professor of physics and live in Bryan, Texas.
And you divide your activities in between teaching and research.
Yes, teaching and research are my activities here at A&M.
Okay.
Why did you originally come here?
And when and why did you originally come here?
When I first came to A&M, I came here as a student back in, this is January of 1946.
And I was, I had gone to school, to college before that time, to a university.
I had gone to Rice before that time.
But my
education had been interrupted by the war, World War II.
And I had spent two years at Rice as a, not in physics or science, but actually as a, well, mainly a liberal arts major in preparation, what I thought would be for the law.
I was preparing what's called a pre-law undergraduate program at Rice, which included a lot of language and economics, but with some math and science, of course.
and philosophy and economics and all those things.
But the war came along, and I was involved with the war for three years or so.
And when I got out of the Army, I had thought a lot about going back to college just before I was about to be discharged.
And I had decided that
that I wanted to study either engineering or science, like physics, something of that sort, instead of law.
I decided against law for reasons which I really can't explain.
I think it was just a matter of drifting away from it.
During the time I was in the Army, I'd had some science.
I'd gone to New York University in a special program, which they called in those days the Army Specialized Training Program, ASTP, which is
kind of known to those who were involved with university work in the Army days.
They picked out people who were interested in going to school and sent some of us to school.
I was in New York University, and I got my first real good physics there in math and things like that.
And I decided that I wanted to go into science, in particular physics, in math.
Well, when I got out of the Army, it was in December of 1945.
And I was leaning toward A&M anyway.
I knew A&M was a good school.
A&M sort of runs in my family.
My brother had gone to A&M, and my uncles, and everybody I knew had gone to A&M except me.
I was the only one who had gone to Rice.
I like Rice just fine.
Rice is a very good school.
Although I don't think it's quite
as great now as I used to think it was for some various completely spurious reasons.
Some of the attitudes the students have at basketball games is pretty bad.
But anyway, I came to A&M because my brother got out of the Army almost immediately after I did.
And he and I decided we'd go to school together here.
And I could come here in mid-year, which was a great advantage, and go in the summers, as you know, or maybe you don't know, at Rice.
They don't have summer school.
And they don't allow students to enter at mid-year.
They don't have a regular semester.
They have a year long.
They don't have students entering in January.
At least they didn't in those days.
And to my knowledge, they still don't.
So these various circumstances led me to come here, at least on a trial basis.
And once I got here, I liked it so much that I wouldn't have considered leaving.
And as I say, I came in January of 1946.
And I came in just before the biggest influx of veterans, so-called veterans, people who had been in the Army or Navy or whatever.
And the January...
influx of veterans was pretty big, but then in the fall, they really came in.
We were three and four to a room, normally we're meant for two, that sort of thing.
But it was good.
We were all pretty, quite serious and interested in our work.
We were all a little older, of course, than most undergraduates were in those days, or most undergraduates had been, rather, I should say.
And I liked A&M very much immediately.
I liked just everything about it.
It was a good place to be.

I got to get away from, for one thing, from home again, which was kind of important to me because I don't think I could have just sat around at home and studied after being away for not so long in the war and all that sort of thing.
And being here, the general atmosphere was conducive to serious work and enjoying being with a bunch of other students.
And of course, we had good times.
We'd go into Houston, visit with our friends.
And at that time, of course, I wasn't married.
I wasn't very young, but I was still young enough to wait to be married.
Nobody had cars except a few guys here and there.
We'd all gang up and either hitchhike or ride in the weekend.
But it was A&M, surprisingly, I'll be able to say A&M's changed a lot.
And I'll just say that, to me, A&M hasn't changed all that much.
A&M has always been a very good school, from my point of view.
In those days it was great because there was the basic spirit, good traditions, things that were fun and worthwhile.
And the same kinds of things are here now.
The difference is other people have joined A&M.

Now, of course, and we'll get to this later on, I'm sure, we have people who are not necessarily in the Corps, but who, I think, by and large, have similar spirits, similar attitudes, and lots of same basic feelings toward an end that the Corps does, and had in those days.
The Corps being almost inclusive.
Of course, as a veteran, we weren't in the Corps.
Most of us weren't.
But I...
Well, I just remembered it as a very good place to work and enjoy fellowship with other students.
And it was academically very sound, challenging to me.
And so I stayed.
I graduated in 1948.
Got a degree in 1948.
I guess it was in June of 48.
I can't think of it.
So then I left A&M.
At that time, A&M's graduate work in physics didn't have the same history or whatever the word is.
It wasn't established as well as the graduate work in physics at certain other universities in the country.
And this was true a lot of places, because A&M wasn't alone in that regard.
So for graduate work, in fact, there hadn't been any PhDs at all granted at A&M in physics.
And I had good advice from Dr. James Potter, who was head of the department then and was for many years subsequently, to go off to graduate school.
And I went to Rice, went back to Rice to go to graduate school in physics.
And I guess it was five years later I got a degree, a Ph.D., in 1953.
Now, I'm not telling you much about the way A&M was in those days, but I have hinted that, of course, it was all male in those days, but at least as far as I remember it was.
I don't know if there were any girls there at all.
There were, of course, ladies, and I know there were lots of married students.
And I knew lots of my friends were married, and I got to know the families and children and so forth.
But I was pretty much all business in those days.
I wasn't a member of any organizations, and I didn't run for any offices of any sort.
I felt that my main goal was to be in school.
And so that's really what I did.
I just went to school.
But I enjoyed the general atmosphere.
And as I say, I made a lot of lifelong friends, people whom I still know well and see often, in some cases, not so often in others, how far away they are and so forth.
But I remember distinctly that the distance between College Station and Bryan in those days
like the distance between two little towns, you really went on a country road.
You went down Texas Avenue to go from here to Bryan.
We used to go into Bryan to go to a picture show now and then.
There was a show downtown, so to speak.
And when you rode along Texas Avenue, you'd ride on a bumpy country highway.
I can't think what to compare it with exactly around here, but it was a turtleback highway.
a road with a lot of trees on either side and deep ditch, deep ditches and windmills and a few farms here and there.
And you go from one town to another, you really knew you went to another town.
They really weren't contiguous cities as they are now at Colley Station and Bryan.
I remember that very distinctly.
I remember that Guyon Hall was used in those days to show movies quite regularly, whereas Guyon Hall doesn't exist anymore.
And there was that movie, and there was a movie at the North Gate, which is still there, the campus theater, which a lot of us used to go to just for fun, especially on Sunday nights.
That was a time to goof off because the long week was ahead.
But that's one of the most distinct memories I have about the community in those days is that really they were a really separate little town, separated.
I don't remember distinctly about College Avenue.
College Avenue may have been more nearly continuous in the sense of residences, but I gather, as I remember, though, there were some vacant lots and some open country in there.
I just beg to remember that.
Because I know going to town, we always seem to go on Highway 6 to go into Bryan.
One thing we used to do was go into...
to a lady's home who had served family-style meals.
We were on a real treat.
There was a lady named Mrs. Ball, whose sister maybe still runs the cafeteria out at the Annex.
I'm not sure about that.
That's the same family, anyway.

Anyway, you'd go to that home, and she had a nice big kitchen in the back, and guys would go in the living room and go into the big dining room there and sit at a table and have family-style meals, which was always a treat.
And, of course, you eat that way.
And the Corps, we didn't.
We weren't in the Corps.
Where did you live?
I lived in various dorms.
My first dorm was dorm 16.
Do they still call them by numbers over here?
Yes, they go up to 12.
No, not 16.
It was 12.
I must have been 12.
I was in room 116.
That's it.
Okay.
Number 16 came to mind.
There was a dorm...
numbered 16, I think, over here.
In fact, what they used to call them by numbers over in the old... See, dorms very much like these are built in the Northgate area.
In fact, they're built at the same time.
Just west of... What's the big old Walton Hall?
West of Walton, there's some dorms that are like the dorms in the core area.
I think there was a dorm 16, 17, 18 over there.
I'm not sure.
Anyway, I lived first in dorm 18, then I lived in dorm 7 and other various dorms over here.
Then I lived in Walton Hall, G ramp, G1, Walton.
And I remember very well those various rooms we lived in.
My brother and I roomed together.
We were a few brother-roommate roommates.
pairs around.
Most brothers broke up, but my brother and I were good friends and got along well.
We're very nearly the same age, close enough.
He's bigger than I am and makes us look the same age, although he's two years younger than I am.
So, uh, and I enjoyed dorm life.
I enjoyed knowing all the guys.
But the dorm life wasn't quite the same as it is in the Corps.
It was different in the sense that it was more informal, of course.
We just, we had
that weren't scheduled as tightly or scheduled as regularly as you are in your regular organized activities in the Corps.
We lived among the Corps, though.
Some of the dorms near us would be Corps dorms, and we were always aware that guys were falling out at certain times and bugles were blowing and things of that sort.
But we never did respond to those bugles.
We weren't required to, fortunately.
But because your schedules were pretty demanding, as I remember, up early and busy, which is fine.
And we were not unfamiliar with that sort of thing, having been in the Army, all of us, for some years.
Knowing what it means to fall out at a certain time and do things on a regular basis.
How did the community population, you know, the people, how did they treat people at A&M?
Did they treat you as a veteran different from the poor?
Or did they kind of look at you all as Aggies?
My general, as I remember, we were all treated the same.
I mean, if you were a student at A&M, it was pretty... For one thing, the population of the two towns...
College Station Bryan, as far as just people that were in the town, was smaller than it is now by a long shot.
I don't know how much smaller, really.
I don't have a good estimate of that.
I'm sure that can be looked up.
But I distinctly remember that College Station was a very small community just around the campus, peripheral to the campus.
And the people treated us all very politely, very, very well.
I remember, for example, hitchhiking.
was routine and comfortable and easy and safe and everybody felt okay about it.
I don't think people do quite the same now.
I mean, it's different now for various reasons.
The big cities are bigger and they have bad reputations for people that do hitchhiking and there's lots of reasons why hitchhiking isn't a very good thing to do anymore.
Whereas in those days, hitchhiking was routine.
We had a place where we stood out there at the east gate and along there and we'd just get in line and then
20 minutes, even if the line was 40 or 50 people long, 20, 30 minutes, you'd be on your way.
And nobody went upstream.
That wasn't fair.
You could go downstream, catch somebody who just thought about it a moment or something.
But I used to get rides into Houston just routinely, you know, and never worry about it.
I don't think I would recommend that for my son, you know.
I don't know what you, do people still hitchhike very much?
Not quite as much as they used to.
Most everybody has a car.
That's one big difference.
In those days, most of us didn't have cars.
I didn't own a car until I was, what, 26 years old, I guess.
Whereas now, people tend to own cars a good deal younger, and it's normal.
Then there would be less hitchhiking.
In those days, there were very few cars on the campus, and some of the parking lots that are in the middle of the campus were just graveled.
this lot 19 out here, right between us and Hart Hall, you know?
Very central parking lot.
That was a gravel, just a little gravel drive.
There may be enough room to accommodate 30 or 40 cars at most.
Now it's all paved and curved, and I don't know how many cars it accommodates, but it's bigger than it was.
So I remember, anyway.
And, of course, we have lots and lots of parking space and still more parking problems, as you know.
I'm sure we all do because of the construction.
But in answer to your question, the people in town, both towns, I thought were very nice.
And I don't think there was any distinction between the Corps and non-reg, what we call non-reg students.
I guess we still call them non-regs.
I don't know.
Civilian students.
And...
I just remember that I was well treated, and I know the Corps was too, because everybody respected the Corps, and still does, of course, very highly.
So, I remember that with pleasure and being very pleasant.
Once you got, what'd you do right after you got your doctorate?
When I first got my doctorate, I had been a consultant at what was then called the Humboldt Oil and Refining Company.
I'm sure you remember when it was called Humboldt.
It was only recently changed to the name Exxon.
I was a consultant during my graduate school days at Rice with what's called the Humboldt Research Labs.
It was called Production Research.
And that was downtown Houston when I first started there.
In fact, it was that way all the time I did
consulting work and summer work for Humboldt.
And then I stayed on that summer after I got my PhD and worked full time for Humboldt.
But in the meantime I had arranged to come back to teach here.
I talked to Dr. Potter and I talked about it and we agreed that there was a position for me here to teach.
So I taught here for one calendar year in 1953
through the August of 54, including the summer, September through August, September 53 through August of 54.
So I was here one calendar year as an assistant professor, and I enjoyed that very much.
I must say, in those days, I felt, see, I wasn't married still, and I was thinking that being unmarried and not being in a,
community that there was an excess of men, not very many girls to meet.
But I thought I should be in an area where there was more convenient social life and so forth.
Ironically, it turns out, however, that I had met the girl that I did marry, finally.
And she was a girl that I had met in Houston.
And fortunately, I did marry.
We did get married.
But at that time, we hadn't planned to get married.
What I did then was I had an opportunity to teach at the University of Missouri, Columbia, Missouri.
And I thought it over, and I said, well, I probably should go ahead and take the opportunity to go to another part of the country.
I had been away off and on anyway, as I mentioned.
Like in the war, I was in Europe and New York and Colorado and California all around.
And I enjoyed being in Texas, but I also enjoyed the opportunity to sample parts, other parts of the world.
And going to the Midwest seemed attractive.
And it was attractive.
I went to the University of Missouri and taught there.
I guess I taught there just eight years.
And I enjoyed it very much.
I got married soon after being up there, Joanne, my wife.
I got married in...
1955, I guess, a year later in June of 55.
And I was real, real young then.
Although I wasn't real old either.
So anyway,
I was there first by myself and then my wife.
We got married and my wife joined me there.
She was there in Missouri.
We were there.
Our son was born in Columbia, Missouri.
We have one son, David.
I guess he was born in 1958.
He's a native Missourian.

then for reasons involving partly my interest, our interest in coming back to Texas and my pleasant memories of A&M and the fact that both my wife and I have family, our only family really, we both have very small families.
Her parents died when she was fairly young.
She has only one close relative, it's a sister in Houston.
And it turns out my parents and brother were at that time my only close family were in Houston too.
So we began to think in terms of the long-term future.
Did we want to be in the Midwest indefinitely, or did we want to go back to an area like here and raise our family, which happened to be one son.
That's the only child we ever had here.
And we decided that coming back here would be better for everybody concerned, including other parts of our family.
So we came back.
And I was very lucky, luckily, an opportunity for me to come back here arose at the right time.
Although I was planning to leave Missouri for two of the years and I even let them know about it.
It was a very orderly resignation from Missouri.
I had been promoted to associate professor there and all that sort of thing.
I felt satisfied that I had performed well enough to
to do anything I wanted to, go elsewhere.
In those days, jobs for physicists were fairly easy to come by, especially if you'd done some research and had a reasonable reputation as a teacher.
So I approached Dr. Potter and mentioned it to him maybe even a year before we finally made the move, or longer than that, I don't know, but we thought about it.
And an opportunity did arise for me to come back, and I came back here in 1962.
And I've been here, we have been here ever since.
So the basic story, the framework of my story here is that I was here as a student in 1946, away for some years after 1948, and then back again in 53, 54.
And during that time, things had changed a little bit.
There was a burgeoning of research activities, which I noticed things had changed in that regard.
The graduate program was really moving to bigger and better things.
But my opportunity to go to Missouri was attractive.
never have regretted doing that, but I'm always glad also to come back, that we came back.
Now we've been here since 1952, which is what, 14 years?
Almost 14 years, I guess.
And I'm very, we're very pleased to be back.
One thing, are we running close to the end of the tape?
No, well, no, we still have a pretty good time.
Okay, well, one thing that's, let's see, I was going to say,
Oh, well, in addition to the attractiveness of A&M itself, as an academic community, which it always has been to me, this general area is attractive to anybody looking in from the outside.
If you're in the Midwest and you don't realize it, if you're here all the time, but if you're away from here, you realize...
that this part of the country is one of the most, well, it's sought after.
It's known to be prosperous.
It's known that the people are vigorous and active and lots is going on here.
By here, I mean generally in the state of Texas and in particular in this part of the state of Texas.
Let's say the south or maybe the south central and southeast part, Houston,
Brown-Dallas axis, so to speak, or whatever, how you want to put it.
So, and this part of the world is looked on in great glowing terms in other parts of the world, other parts of the country.

And I was pleased to know that that was a place where I had been and I knew well, and people who visit here from, say, my university there at the University of Missouri would always come back and say, hey, that's really some place down there.

And a lot of people I knew would come to A&M, and they'd come back with glowing terms about A&M, which always pleased me, because that's where I had been, and that was my home, my alma mater, and so forth.
And you don't realize this until you get away from it, how highly thought of.
We're all very proud of A&M, of course, but it's very nice to know that A&M looks good from a distance, too.
which is something you always can be sure of unless you go to that distance and talk to people.
And that was one of the things, that general prosperity, the general attitude of people in this part of the country, I thought was reassuring for the future.
And I think that has been borne out as you see what's happening to A&M now.
When we first came back to A&M, there were some frustrations, frankly.

I remember distinctly having slightly different standards about such things as libraries, academic participation and student participation in governance, having faculty and student senates to speak up about certain things and have the regular opportunities to do so.
And when I first came back to A&M in 1962,
I guess, politically aware than I had been before.
And some of the frustrations were, I thought, and I still think, well-founded.
I'm saying frustrations in the sense that we had aspirations to be more active as a faculty
And we had aspirations for the student body, as citizens of the community, to have an input to what's going on and what should be done.
And as you know, we now have a very active, perhaps hyperactive, that depends on whose opinions you listen to,
student senates and things of that sort, all sorts of student activities which involve making decisions and influencing decisions at policy level.
And I believe in that sort of thing very strongly.

I think that at least people should have their say and then have a regular way to say it, other than just to go around mumbling to each other and complaining to each other causes more trouble, I think, than to have open forums.
and discussions with the administration and so forth.
And we've made great progress in that regard.
Mr. Rutter was a very good president in many ways.
But in other ways, I think, frankly, that he wasn't the very good president of the university.
It may have been that his way to lead us from one era to another was to be
benevolent autocrat.
He wasn't.
